'''Hans J. Hofmann''' (3 October 1936, [[Kiel]], Germany – 19 May 2010, [[Montreal|Montreal, Quebec]], Canada) was a [[Paleontology|paleontologist]], specializing in the study of [[Precambrian]] [[fossils]] using [[Computer simulation|computer modelling]] and image analysis to quantify [[Comparative anatomy|morphologic attributes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geotop.ca/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=992&Itemid=113&lang=en|title=Passing of paleontologist Hans J. Hofmann (1936-2010)|year=2010|publisher=GEOTOP|accessdate=19 January 2012}}{{dead link|date=October 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/paleontologist-hans-hofmann-filled-an-evolutionary-gap-by-finding-evidence-of-early-life-in-ancient-rocks/article1656734/Obituary Obituary in Toronto Globe and Mail, 29 July 2010. ''Paleontologist Hans Hofmann filled an evolutionary gap by finding evidence of early life in ancient rocks''.] Accessed 16 August 2010.</ref><ref name="RSC">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsc.ca/documents/HofmannHansJorgElectedin200219362010_000.pdf|title=Obituaries of deceased fellows: Hans Jorg Hofmann|last=Narbonne|first=Guy|publisher=[[Royal Society of Canada]]|accessdate=19 January 2012}}</ref>
Born in Germany, Hofmann immigrated to Montreal, Quebec, Canada and studied geology at [[McGill University]], where he earned a Ph.D. under the supervision of [[T. H. Clark]]. He taught for three years at the [[University of Cincinnati]] and then worked at the [[Geological Survey of Canada]]. He was a professor in the geology department of the [[Université de Montréal]] for 31 years (1969–2000). He spent the last ten years of his life as a researcher in the [[Redpath Museum]] and an adjunct professor in the Department of Earth and Planetary Sciences at McGill.<ref name="RSC"/>
The [[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences]] noted him for, "his pioneering discoveries of fossils that have illuminated life's early evolution, from [[Archean]] [[stromatolites]] and [[Proterozoic]] [[cyanobacteria]], to the rise of multicellular organisms."<ref name="RSC"/><ref name=Walcott/>
Hofmann’s contributions have shed light on the [[Biology|biologic]], [[Stratigraphy|stratigraphic]], and [[evolution]]ary significance of various stromatolites, microfossils, macrofossils, and [[trace fossil]]s.
==Awards== *1995, Awarded the [[Willet G. Miller Medal]] by the [[Royal Society of Canada]]<ref name="RSC"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsc.ca/awards_Willet_G_Miller_Medal_winner.php|title=Willet G. Miller Medal|publisher=[[Royal Society of Canada]]|accessdate=19 January 2012}}</ref> *2002, Awarded the [[Charles Doolittle Walcott Medal]] by the [[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences]]<ref name=Walcott>{{cite web|title=Charles Doolittle Walcott Medal|url=http://www.nasonline.org/site/PageServer?pagename=AWARDS_walcott|publisher=National Academy of Sciences|accessdate=14 February 2011}}</ref>
