{{Infobox artwork | title = Lewis and Clark Memorial Column | image_file = File:Pdx washpark lewisandclark memorial sw.jpeg | caption = The sculpture in 2006, viewed from the southwest | image_size = | alt = | other_language_1 = | other_title_1 = | other_language_2 = | other_title_2 = | artist = | catalogue = | year = {{start date|1908}} | type = Sculpture | material = Snake River granite, bronze | subject = | height_metric = | height_imperial = 34.5 | diameter_metric = | diameter_imperial = 2.5 | dimensions = | dimensions_ref = | metric_unit = m<!--don't leave blank—either don't include it, or include the default cm. --> | imperial_unit = ft<!--don't leave blank—either don't include it, or include the default in. --> | condition = "Well maintained" (1993) | city = [[Portland, Oregon]], United States | museum = | accession = | pushpin_map = Portland downtown | pushpin_map_caption= Location in Portland, Oregon | map_size = | coordinates = {{coord|45.521388|-122.70139|type:landmark_region:US-OR|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | owner = City of Portland's Metropolitan Arts Commission | url = <!--{{URL|example.com}} Only for official web pages--> }} The '''''Lewis and Clark Memorial Column''''' is an outdoor monument by artist Otto Schumann, dedicated to [[Meriwether Lewis]] and [[William Clark (explorer)|William Clark]] for [[Lewis and Clark Expedition|their expedition]] and located at [[Washington Park (Portland, Oregon)|Washington Park]] in [[Portland, Oregon]].
==Description== The sculpture, made of Snake River granite, is a Classical column with a sphere on top. It is approximately 34 feet, 6 inches tall, with a diameter of 2.5 feet. The obelisk sits on a square base that is approximately 5 feet, 5 inches tall. The base's sides display bronze seals for the states of [[Oregon]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], [[Idaho]] and [[Montana]], which once comprised the [[Oregon Territory]]. An illuminated path leads up the monument. According to the [[Smithsonian Institution]], the work is administered by City of Portland's Metropolitan Arts Commission.<ref name=SI>{{cite web|title=Lewis and Clark Memorial Column, (sculpture).|url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!324193~!0#focus|publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution]]|accessdate=September 29, 2014}}</ref>
==History== The memorial was commissioned around 1902 by the Lewis & Clark Exposition Commission for approximately $10,500 as a "gift of the people of Oregon in memory" of the duo. President [[Theodore Roosevelt]] laid the first cornerstone on May 21, 1903, and the piece was completed and dedicated in 1908. It was surveyed and considered "well maintained" by Smithsonian's "[[Save Outdoor Sculpture!]]" program in November 1993.<ref name=SI/>
